<subSubSection pageId="25" pageNumber="86" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="25.[151,1437,1677,2028]" pageId="25" pageNumber="86">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,1894,1920]" pageId="25" pageNumber="86">Remarks.</emphasis>
I have examined the 
<typeStatus box="[555,656,1894,1920]" pageId="25" pageNumber="86">holotype</typeStatus>
, including the male genitalia, of 
<taxonomicName authority="(RBINS)" baseAuthorityName="RBINS" box="[1024,1257,1894,1920]" class="Insecta" family="Hydrochidae" genus="Hydrochus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="25" pageNumber="86" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="coeneni">
<emphasis box="[1024,1145,1895,1920]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="86">H. coeneni</emphasis>
(RBINS)
</taxonomicName>
. The male genitalia has the tips of the parameres sheared off—by a previous worker. The remainder of the male genitalia, including the basal piece, are distinctively shaped, allowing the identification. The male genitalia drawing of 
<bibRefCitation author="Makhan, D." box="[1263,1436,1966,1992]" pageId="25" pageNumber="86" pagination="95 - 103" refId="ref12274" refString="Makhan, D. (1992) Twelve new Hydrochus - species from South America. Phegea, 20 (2), 95 - 103." type="journal article" year="1992">Makhan (1992)</bibRefCitation>
shows the paramere tips to be present, but the drawing is very generalized, and only one view is given.
</paragraph>
